    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nCurrently `vim.system` throws an error when `uv.spawn` fails, with bespoke error messages when\n1. the specified `cwd` does not exist\n2. the specified `cmd[1]` is not executable\n\nThis is good for direct (sync and async) use but leads to issues when wrapped in `vim.async` (or its vendored predecessors), where the `error` kills the coroutine, leading to hangs and preventing the useful error message being propagated to the user. (Exhibit A: https://github.com/nvim-treesitter/nvim-treesitter/issues/8010)\n\nWhile the checks for 1. and 2. could be duplicated at the call site before calling the wrapped `vim.system` call, this seems wasteful and in any case does not address other possible `uv.spawn` failures. (To be clear, I am concerned here with the general situation, not (just) the linked issue specifically.)\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nAdd an option to `vim.system` that makes it always return a proper `SystemObj`, which contains any `uv.spawn` error message (not necessarily prettied up) as `result.stderr`.",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
